WEBVTT

00:07.145 --> 00:10.320
[ Wolves howling ]

00:10.355 --> 00:15.670
♪♪

00:15.705 --> 00:18.052
Narrator:
Previously on "Mountain Men"...

00:18.087 --> 00:20.123
Marty: I ain't much
of a beaver trapper today.

00:20.158 --> 00:22.608
Narrator: ...Marty fights
for every last dollar.

00:22.643 --> 00:26.785
Marty: It's late in the season,
and I still hardly have any fur.

00:26.819 --> 00:28.373
But you got to stick to it.

00:28.407 --> 00:30.582
Nothing worthwhile
is gonna come easy.

00:31.790 --> 00:34.655
Narrator: A violent storm
leaves Brent stranded.

00:34.689 --> 00:36.657
Brent: I got to find a place
to hunker down.

00:36.691 --> 00:41.110
It won't be a five-star hotel,
but it should keep me alive.

00:42.111 --> 00:44.078
Narrator:
And Morgan turns a poacher...

00:44.113 --> 00:46.287
Son of a bitch!
Got it!

00:46.322 --> 00:48.841
Narrator: ...into a prize.

00:48.876 --> 00:50.878
That's a nice piece
of fur there.

00:50.912 --> 00:53.156
It's real warm stuff.

00:53.191 --> 01:03.235
And I'm pretty happy
with how it came out.

01:03.235 --> 01:16.145
And I'm pretty happy
with how it came out.

01:16.179 --> 01:18.181
♪♪

01:18.216 --> 01:20.494
Narrator: 200 miles
south of the Arctic Circle

01:20.528 --> 01:23.324
in the Great Alaska Range,

01:23.359 --> 01:26.258
a sudden warm spell transforms
the winter landscape

01:26.293 --> 01:28.053
weeks ahead of schedule.

01:28.088 --> 01:30.849
♪♪

01:30.883 --> 01:34.059
With temperatures hovering
at a balmy 50 degrees,

01:34.094 --> 01:36.199
the three-foot snowpack
that covered the ground

01:36.234 --> 01:39.754
just five days ago
is nearly gone.

01:39.789 --> 01:41.825
An early thaw is usually
a welcome relief

01:41.860 --> 01:43.137
for Morgan Beasley,

01:43.172 --> 01:47.452
but this year,
it may be a big problem.

01:47.486 --> 01:50.282
Morgan: We've got a regularly
scheduled flight come in

01:50.317 --> 01:51.939
and bring us
some needed supplies,

01:51.973 --> 01:54.044
you know,
chief among which is fuel.

01:55.736 --> 01:57.186
I've been milling
a lot of lumber.

01:57.220 --> 02:01.086
We've got, you know, a whole
list of projects for the spring.

02:01.121 --> 02:03.882
All that basically
requires gasoline.

02:03.916 --> 02:06.333
See, I'm down to like
a gallon of fuel there.

02:06.367 --> 02:09.853
And the saws are basically
empty right now.

02:09.888 --> 02:12.062
Narrator: Morgan has
a prearranged fuel drop

02:12.097 --> 02:14.858
that flies in twice a year
along a local flight path

02:14.893 --> 02:17.896
just a few miles
from his homestead.

02:17.930 --> 02:20.761
His next delivery is due
to arrive tomorrow,

02:20.795 --> 02:22.176
but to make the stop,

02:22.211 --> 02:25.490
the pilot has to be
able to land on ice.

02:25.524 --> 02:28.424
Morgan: That lake's about
five or six miles away,

02:28.458 --> 02:30.184
and it's the closest place

02:30.219 --> 02:33.843
where a ski-equipped airplane
can land.

02:33.877 --> 02:36.086
Got these skis here.

02:36.121 --> 02:39.883
This will be the longest trip
I've tried to take them on.

02:39.918 --> 02:43.024
Narrator: The trek to the drop
zone takes half an Alaskan day,

02:43.059 --> 02:45.303
so Morgan plans
to camp out overnight

02:45.337 --> 02:48.237
to meet the plane
bright and early.

02:48.271 --> 02:51.412
Quite a number of miles there,
so I'm gonna get moving.

02:51.447 --> 02:56.969
♪♪

02:57.004 --> 03:02.665
♪♪

03:02.699 --> 03:03.735
Ooh.

03:06.324 --> 03:08.705
This wasn't here yesterday.

03:08.740 --> 03:12.053
This ice just fell out,
you know, yesterday afternoon,

03:12.088 --> 03:15.125
maybe last night.

03:15.160 --> 03:16.506
Creeks are opening up.

03:16.541 --> 03:19.647
I mean, this is just right
near the house, too.

03:19.682 --> 03:22.650
I hope it's not any worse.

03:22.685 --> 03:24.100
I'm worried now.

03:24.134 --> 03:26.413
This is a ton of water
for this time of year,

03:26.447 --> 03:29.726
and if this is happening here,
what's happening at the lake?

03:29.761 --> 03:33.074
I'm gonna be making the call
on whether that lake ice

03:33.109 --> 03:35.456
is safe to land on or not.

03:35.491 --> 03:37.665
And if I make a bad call,

03:37.700 --> 03:40.358
I could wreck a plane
or hurt somebody.

03:40.392 --> 03:41.428
It's pretty high stakes,

03:41.462 --> 03:43.568
and I got to make sure
the ice is good.

03:43.602 --> 03:48.228
♪♪

03:48.262 --> 03:49.884
Where did all this come from?

03:49.919 --> 03:52.370
Look at all this water.

03:52.404 --> 04:00.032
♪♪

04:00.067 --> 04:02.414
It's kind of, like,
a couple feet of water

04:02.449 --> 04:05.072
flowing over
a couple feet of slush

04:05.106 --> 04:08.040
and honeycombed old rotten snow.

04:08.075 --> 04:09.628
So you could go in there,
but you might --

04:09.663 --> 04:12.804
you might go in much deeper
than you think you will.

04:12.838 --> 04:14.840
Hope it doesn't break.

04:17.222 --> 04:18.154
Oh!

04:18.188 --> 04:20.743
Whew, nice.

04:20.777 --> 04:23.297
Kept my feet dry.

04:23.332 --> 04:24.678
Ooh.

04:24.712 --> 04:31.340
♪♪

04:31.374 --> 04:33.790
All right.
Made it across that.

04:33.825 --> 04:36.034
And if there's this
much water flowing here,

04:36.068 --> 04:38.830
I don't know what it's gonna be
doing at the pond,

04:38.864 --> 04:40.797
so I better get moving.

04:40.832 --> 04:50.807
♪♪

04:50.842 --> 05:00.783
♪♪

05:00.817 --> 05:02.578
Ooh.

05:02.612 --> 05:05.477
Aw [bleep]

05:05.512 --> 05:06.858
That's not good.

05:06.892 --> 05:09.723
♪♪

05:09.757 --> 05:11.897
Overflow on the lake.

05:11.932 --> 05:21.907
♪♪

05:21.942 --> 05:26.222
♪♪

05:26.256 --> 05:28.811
Narrator:
In Montana's Yaak Valley,

05:28.845 --> 05:31.676
Tom Oar is on track
for the most successful season

05:31.710 --> 05:34.230
he's had in nearly five years,

05:34.264 --> 05:36.163
and the early thaw
is an opportunity

05:36.197 --> 05:38.476
to add to the bounty.

05:38.510 --> 05:40.236
Tom:
The water just opened.

05:40.270 --> 05:42.756
The ice just went out
two days ago.

05:42.790 --> 05:46.863
And I jumped right in there
right away and put traps in.

05:46.898 --> 05:49.832
This should be an ideal time.

05:49.866 --> 05:52.559
The critters that are
trapped underneath the ice

05:52.593 --> 05:55.320
when it's froze,
they enjoy to come out

05:55.355 --> 05:58.772
and to be able to breathe
fresh air above the ice.

05:58.806 --> 06:01.947
So it makes everybody
real active.

06:01.982 --> 06:05.019
Narrator:
With Sean's help running the
productive Kootenai River line,

06:05.054 --> 06:08.333
Tom's focus is
on specialty commissions

06:08.368 --> 06:09.886
that bring in top dollar.

06:09.921 --> 06:19.896
♪♪

06:19.931 --> 06:23.244
♪♪

06:23.279 --> 06:24.487
All right.

06:27.283 --> 06:29.009
This is --
This is what we're after.

06:29.043 --> 06:31.391
This is -- This is a muskrat.

06:32.495 --> 06:34.946
One drowned muskrat.

06:34.980 --> 06:39.640
We've got an order for a muskrat
hat now for a guy back in Ohio.

06:39.675 --> 06:42.988
Takes about five muskrats
to make a hat.

06:43.023 --> 06:46.647
♪♪

06:46.682 --> 06:48.822
I got more traps to check.

06:50.927 --> 06:54.793
I've been trapping for 50 years,
and no better satisfaction

06:54.828 --> 06:58.176
than taking an animal
out of the bush

06:58.210 --> 07:00.903
by -- by making him step
in a circle

07:00.937 --> 07:03.008
like that that you
created yourself.

07:03.043 --> 07:06.564
♪♪

07:06.598 --> 07:08.980
Boy, we got another one.

07:10.982 --> 07:13.709
[ Laughs ]

07:13.743 --> 07:16.436
On the raw fur market,
if I went out

07:16.470 --> 07:18.714
and caught five muskrats
and skinned them

07:18.748 --> 07:20.647
and stretched them
and dried them,

07:20.681 --> 07:23.373
sent them to the raw fur trade,

07:23.408 --> 07:27.619
if I was lucky, I'd get
5 bucks a piece for them.

07:27.654 --> 07:30.691
Let me get this trap set.

07:30.726 --> 07:32.728
Get it back in there.

07:32.762 --> 07:37.008
Those same five muskrats
will make a muskrat hat

07:37.042 --> 07:40.356
that I can sell for $250.

07:40.390 --> 07:45.775
So why sell them 5 muskrats
for 25 bucks, you know,

07:45.810 --> 07:49.158
when just a little extra work,

07:49.192 --> 07:51.505
you can --
you can make more money?

07:51.540 --> 07:55.095
That's what we're after.

07:55.129 --> 08:05.105
♪♪

08:05.139 --> 08:07.763
♪♪

08:07.797 --> 08:11.283
Narrator: On Alaska's rugged
southern coast,

08:11.318 --> 08:14.252
Brent Jameson is back to work
building a permanent foothold

08:14.286 --> 08:16.012
on his family property...

08:16.047 --> 08:17.324
There we go.

08:17.358 --> 08:20.258
...where his attempt to resettle
after his 17-year absence

08:20.292 --> 08:23.468
has required weeks
of grueling work.

08:23.503 --> 08:27.783
My return here is kind of
a return to myself in some ways,

08:27.817 --> 08:31.269
at least the parts of myself
that I'm proudest of.

08:31.303 --> 08:33.374
[ Hammering ]

08:33.409 --> 08:35.376
I remember talking about
building here one day

08:35.411 --> 08:36.826
with my dad.

08:36.861 --> 08:41.417
And I'm just really grateful
to be in this area, on my land,

08:41.451 --> 08:43.108
and finally have a chance
to build on it.

08:43.143 --> 08:46.249
Narrator: Brent's building
a cabin to call home.

08:46.284 --> 08:49.218
So far, he's erected
a 400-square-foot frame

08:49.252 --> 08:51.427
with an elevated loft.

08:51.461 --> 08:53.912
Brent: I got to haul
my ridgeboard up here.

08:53.947 --> 08:58.710
Narrator: Today, it's time to
begin construction on the roof,

08:58.745 --> 09:02.093
a critical job that hinges
on one single piece of timber --

09:02.127 --> 09:03.543
the ridge beam.

09:03.577 --> 09:07.063
This is what all the rafters
are gonna tie into,

09:07.098 --> 09:11.447
and this is gonna be
sitting the highest

09:11.481 --> 09:13.587
for the peak of my roof.

09:13.622 --> 09:16.072
♪♪

09:16.107 --> 09:18.765
Narrator: The 20-foot beam
weighs nearly 200 pounds

09:18.799 --> 09:22.182
and must be mounted
12 feet off the ground.

09:22.216 --> 09:26.048
It's gonna go from
that post to this post.

09:26.082 --> 09:28.740
I'm gonna have to brace it
on my shoulder

09:28.775 --> 09:33.918
and somehow fit it into
the notch on the front post.

09:33.952 --> 09:38.578
So what I'm gonna do
is build a little bridge.

09:38.612 --> 09:40.614
Narrator:
To reach the far post,

09:40.649 --> 09:43.652
Brent builds a makeshift
scaffold to cross the gap.

09:43.686 --> 09:48.760
The boards provide a surface
just 12 inches wide.

09:48.795 --> 09:50.451
All right.

09:50.486 --> 09:52.971
Try to lift this up
into place here.

09:53.006 --> 09:58.287
♪♪

09:58.321 --> 10:02.636
I have to walk out on this plank
with this heavy board

10:02.671 --> 10:04.534
and try to fit it in that notch.

10:04.569 --> 10:11.852
♪♪

10:11.887 --> 10:14.683
It's not a good time
to be afraid of heights.

10:14.717 --> 10:19.653
♪♪

10:19.688 --> 10:20.965
Okay.

10:20.999 --> 10:22.518
Okay.

10:22.552 --> 10:23.726
If I fall from this height,

10:23.761 --> 10:25.521
I'm for sure gonna
break something.

10:25.555 --> 10:28.766
A good gust of wind, or
if my ridgepost at the far end

10:28.800 --> 10:31.216
isn't nailed in right,
it could all come crashing down.

10:31.251 --> 10:34.495
♪♪

10:34.530 --> 10:36.774
Gosh, this feels so sketchy.

10:45.368 --> 10:49.027
here slowly and carefully

10:49.062 --> 10:50.822
because if I fall
from this height even,

10:50.857 --> 10:52.513
I could easily hurt myself.

10:52.548 --> 10:55.896
♪♪

10:55.931 --> 10:58.588
Being extra careful.

10:58.623 --> 11:00.107
All right.

11:00.142 --> 11:01.695
That should sit in there
for a second,

11:01.730 --> 11:03.421
give me time
to get this up and nailed.

11:03.455 --> 11:12.257
♪♪

11:12.292 --> 11:13.396
[ Grunts ]

11:13.431 --> 11:17.642
♪♪

11:17.677 --> 11:19.644
[ Grunts ]

11:19.679 --> 11:21.335
[ Hammering ]

11:25.098 --> 11:26.444
Ridgeboard's in.

11:26.478 --> 11:27.687
[ Sniffles ]

11:27.721 --> 11:30.690
That means...

11:30.724 --> 11:32.484
it's time
to build some rafters.

11:32.519 --> 11:37.248
Narrator: The ridge beam forms
the spine of the cabin roof,

11:37.282 --> 11:39.940
which will be braced
with 22 12-foot rafters

11:39.975 --> 11:43.288
that Brent's pre-cut.

11:43.323 --> 11:46.913
So we got to hammer
this nail down first.

11:46.947 --> 11:49.156
[ Hammering ]

11:50.917 --> 11:52.642
There we go.

11:52.677 --> 11:55.024
There's a flush board.

11:55.059 --> 11:56.474
[ Grunts ]

11:56.508 --> 11:58.096
Got to make sure she's lined up
on the other side

11:58.131 --> 12:00.236
of my ridgeboard here

12:00.271 --> 12:03.826
and nail it in there.

12:03.861 --> 12:06.587
Narrator: The roof frame
is exposed to the elements

12:06.622 --> 12:10.005
and vulnerable to high winds
until it's fully supported,

12:10.039 --> 12:14.009
so there's no stopping until
all the rafters are in place.

12:14.043 --> 12:15.286
All right.
[ Sniffles ]

12:15.320 --> 12:17.288
That's the first rafter in.

12:17.322 --> 12:20.256
Gonna be rinse and repeat here
for a while.

12:20.291 --> 12:26.366
♪♪

12:26.400 --> 12:27.781
It's starting to snow.

12:27.816 --> 12:34.098
♪♪

12:34.132 --> 12:37.687
But as long as I can
get the rafters up

12:37.722 --> 12:40.207
before dark I should be good.

12:40.242 --> 12:41.830
It's kind of changing
how I have to work.

12:41.864 --> 12:43.832
I have to be much more careful.

12:43.866 --> 12:50.700
♪♪

12:50.735 --> 12:52.047
Everything is super slick,

12:52.081 --> 12:55.982
so slow and steady
is the ticket.

12:56.016 --> 13:03.921
♪♪

13:03.955 --> 13:06.924
Nothing like building
[chuckling] through a snowstorm.

13:06.958 --> 13:09.340
Well, the storm could get worse,

13:09.374 --> 13:12.205
but right now my mind
is fixed on getting it done

13:12.239 --> 13:13.275
no matter what.

13:13.309 --> 13:14.621
I don't really have
another option.

13:14.655 --> 13:20.523
♪♪

13:20.558 --> 13:26.426
♪♪

13:26.460 --> 13:29.222
[ Wind gusting ]

13:29.256 --> 13:34.020
Narrator:
In the foothills of Montana's
Tobacco Root Mountains...

13:34.054 --> 13:35.262
an early change in the weather

13:35.297 --> 13:38.369
is a disruption
for lion hunter Rich Lewis.

13:38.403 --> 13:39.715
Rich:
It's been really a weird winter.

13:39.749 --> 13:41.890
We had a really cold spell
in January.

13:41.924 --> 13:44.616
It's on record one of
the coldest winters we've had.

13:44.651 --> 13:46.480
But it's crazy, we had
a chinook come in here

13:46.515 --> 13:47.757
and just melt the snow,

13:47.792 --> 13:50.864
and it makes it difficult
to find a lion track.

13:50.899 --> 13:52.417
Narrator:
Without snow on the ground,

13:52.452 --> 13:55.489
Rich's predator patrol
is on hold.

13:55.524 --> 13:57.284
There's a little sign here.

13:57.319 --> 13:59.217
Narrator:
But Rich isn't wasting time.

13:59.252 --> 14:00.978
He's taking advantage
of the slowdown

14:01.012 --> 14:02.772
to hunt for his next meal.

14:02.807 --> 14:04.395
Well, I know there's got to be
some rabbits around here.

14:04.429 --> 14:06.638
It's just too good,
all the grass cover.

14:06.673 --> 14:08.537
They can come out and feed
and then run back in

14:08.571 --> 14:11.471
if they see an eagle
flying over.

14:11.505 --> 14:13.438
Hunting season was tough
this year.

14:13.473 --> 14:14.957
I didn't get an elk or a deer.

14:14.992 --> 14:16.614
But I've got to survive,

14:16.648 --> 14:18.650
so I've got to find
another food source

14:18.685 --> 14:21.688
and get some food on the table.

14:21.722 --> 14:23.069
I'm focusing on rabbits,

14:23.103 --> 14:26.003
and rabbits is one
of the easiest animals to trap.

14:26.037 --> 14:27.590
Rabbits like to go
back and forth.

14:27.625 --> 14:29.799
They use the same trail.

14:29.834 --> 14:32.492
That looks like a good spot
right there.

14:32.526 --> 14:34.666
Rabbit's kind of got a house
in there.

14:36.703 --> 14:38.774
You kind of got
to look at the area,

14:38.808 --> 14:40.845
and you got to kind
of think like a rabbit.

14:40.880 --> 14:44.987
Got some grain from the horses
and a little corn.

14:45.022 --> 14:46.886
And that's the one thing
in trapping,

14:46.920 --> 14:48.853
I always think like
an animal and figure out,

14:48.888 --> 14:50.993
well, which way would I go
or what would I do?

14:51.028 --> 14:53.754
So you got to really look
the situation over.

14:53.789 --> 14:55.584
♪♪

14:55.618 --> 14:57.689
Metal traps have been around
for hundreds of years.

14:57.724 --> 14:59.001
That's an old tradition,

14:59.036 --> 15:01.038
trappers from way back when,
you know?

15:01.072 --> 15:04.213
So it's an easy,
simple way to do something

15:04.248 --> 15:06.457
where you can set
a lot of traps.

15:06.491 --> 15:07.872
Well, I'm gonna try
something different.

15:07.907 --> 15:09.563
I'm gonna make a pit
where a rabbit,

15:09.598 --> 15:13.464
if it runs across,
it might fall through.

15:13.498 --> 15:15.811
Narrator: Pit trapping is one
of the most primitive ways

15:15.845 --> 15:18.227
to catch small game,

15:18.262 --> 15:20.505
but rabbits are strong jumpers,

15:20.540 --> 15:22.956
so the pit must be
at least three feet deep

15:22.991 --> 15:25.683
and well camouflaged.

15:25.717 --> 15:26.926
Rich:
The reason I chose this is

15:26.960 --> 15:28.962
because there's two game trails,

15:28.997 --> 15:31.378
and rabbits are gonna use
the trail regardless.

15:31.413 --> 15:34.209
Coyote might chase a rabbit
right through here.

15:34.243 --> 15:37.660
He falls in,
and, uh, I've got him.

15:37.695 --> 15:40.905
♪♪

15:40.940 --> 15:44.184
I want to take some willows
and make, like, a netting.

15:44.219 --> 15:48.188
It's gonna be real thin and
blended in so it looks natural.

15:48.223 --> 15:54.470
♪♪

15:54.505 --> 15:57.577
It's not gonna take very much
weight to fall through,

15:57.611 --> 16:00.511
and it's deep enough where
a rabbit can't get out of it.

16:00.545 --> 16:06.068
♪♪

16:06.103 --> 16:08.243
Narrator: Sticks and logs create
a natural funnel

16:08.277 --> 16:11.211
to help steer the rabbit
toward the trap.

16:11.246 --> 16:13.696
Rich: When you're trapping
rabbits, you narrow it down

16:13.731 --> 16:16.872
to where the rabbit has to go
forward 'cause he can't back up.

16:16.906 --> 16:19.909
The way his legs are built,
they can only go forward.

16:19.944 --> 16:22.015
So he's gonna go into my trap
no matter what.

16:22.050 --> 16:23.637
He has to.

16:23.672 --> 16:25.639
All right.
Here is pretty weak.

16:25.674 --> 16:27.503
I'm gonna put a little food
right here.

16:27.538 --> 16:30.817
So rabbit comes running
through here and falls in,

16:30.851 --> 16:32.543
I've got him.

16:32.577 --> 16:36.064
Narrator:
If the trap works, the rabbit
will be a beacon for predators.

16:36.098 --> 16:40.275
So Rich will need to remain
vigilant over his catch.

16:40.309 --> 16:42.277
Might be squealing
'cause it's in the trap,

16:42.311 --> 16:44.555
and a predator will come
and get it before I do.

16:44.589 --> 16:46.005
But I'll keep checking on them,

16:46.039 --> 16:48.145
so it won't be in there
very long.

16:48.179 --> 16:49.767
All righty.

16:49.801 --> 16:52.011
See what happens.

16:56.325 --> 16:56.774
Narrator: Coming up...

16:56.808 --> 16:59.087
♪♪

16:59.121 --> 17:01.261
Narrator:
In the Great Alaska Range...

17:01.296 --> 17:10.891
♪♪

17:10.926 --> 17:14.136
Morgan:
Whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa.

17:14.171 --> 17:16.552
[ Chuckles ]

17:16.587 --> 17:18.244
Hold on, hold on.

17:18.278 --> 17:20.867
It just cracked
all over the place.

17:20.901 --> 17:23.007
♪♪

17:23.042 --> 17:26.390
Narrator:
...Morgan's plans for
a fuel drop are in meltdown.

17:26.424 --> 17:29.772
♪♪

17:29.807 --> 17:31.257
Morgan: Yeah, you can see
the overflow here

17:31.291 --> 17:35.364
is flowing out
onto the lake ice.

17:35.399 --> 17:37.504
Oh, God. Yeah.
[ Laughs ]

17:37.539 --> 17:39.437
There's, like,
a big, deep channel there

17:39.472 --> 17:42.578
that's flowing out
and infiltrating all that ice

17:42.613 --> 17:47.342
and weakening it
and causing it crack.

17:47.376 --> 17:49.620
Narrator: Overflow occurs
when water from below

17:49.654 --> 17:52.864
breaks through the frozen
surface and floods it.

17:52.899 --> 17:55.764
It's a telltale sign
that ice is unstable,

17:55.798 --> 17:59.802
a factor that could derail
tomorrow's critical supply drop.

17:59.837 --> 18:03.703
Morgan: I've got to make sure
that the lake ice is still good

18:03.737 --> 18:06.292
'cause that's where the pilot
wants to land, is on this lake.

18:06.326 --> 18:08.121
It's long enough
for his airplane.

18:08.156 --> 18:10.261
If a plane were to land
on something like this,

18:10.296 --> 18:13.126
it's just ice
over a bunch of water.

18:13.161 --> 18:14.748
Even if there's ice
underneath of it,

18:14.783 --> 18:16.371
they'll break through
into that water,

18:16.405 --> 18:19.857
and it could flip him over
or at least get him stuck.

18:19.891 --> 18:23.343
And that's not what we want,
so I've got to find a way

18:23.378 --> 18:26.657
a little further out
onto the colder, thicker ice.

18:30.109 --> 18:33.112
Usually there's more overflow
around the edges of the lake,

18:33.146 --> 18:35.010
and the ice tends to be
a little better

18:35.044 --> 18:36.391
in the middle of the lake.

18:36.425 --> 18:39.808
So I'm gonna go out
and try to assess its strength.

18:39.842 --> 18:41.741
Hopefully out there
in the center of the lake

18:41.775 --> 18:44.157
is a section of good, solid ice.

18:44.192 --> 18:46.642
♪♪

18:46.677 --> 18:50.163
[ Tapping ]

18:50.198 --> 18:52.303
Listening to this -- Whoa.

18:52.338 --> 18:54.754
♪♪

18:54.788 --> 18:56.894
[ Tapping ]

18:58.240 --> 19:00.932
Narrator: To support the weight
of a 1-ton plane,

19:00.967 --> 19:04.350
the ice must be at least
a full foot thick.

19:04.384 --> 19:06.317
Come on, Rufus.

19:08.008 --> 19:09.527
You know, if I can't
find good ice,

19:09.562 --> 19:10.804
or it seems like the overflow's

19:10.839 --> 19:12.703
kind of infiltrated
the whole lake,

19:12.737 --> 19:15.568
then we'll just have
to put a big X out there

19:15.602 --> 19:17.949
and wave the pilot off.

19:17.984 --> 19:20.676
And that means we don't get
our stuff, especially our fuel.

19:20.711 --> 19:21.884
That's critical.

19:25.025 --> 19:32.516
♪♪

19:32.550 --> 19:34.173
Narrator: In Montana...

19:34.207 --> 19:36.209
♪♪

19:36.244 --> 19:38.591
...an early thaw
is an opportunity for Rich

19:38.625 --> 19:41.732
to make up for lost time.

19:41.766 --> 19:43.872
After several failed
hunting attempts

19:43.906 --> 19:45.943
left him with an empty larder,

19:45.977 --> 19:50.637
he survived nearly
the entire winter on small game

19:50.672 --> 19:53.502
and now is redoubling
his efforts

19:53.537 --> 19:57.092
to snag his next meal.

19:57.126 --> 19:58.300
Rich:
I thought I'd come up here,

19:58.335 --> 20:00.026
and maybe I could just catch
a rabbit out here.

20:00.060 --> 20:01.372
These brush piles
are really good.

20:01.407 --> 20:03.132
Rabbits will go underneath
there and hide.

20:03.167 --> 20:05.376
So maybe I can get
a shot at one.

20:08.483 --> 20:10.312
Narrator:
While letting his traps soak,

20:10.347 --> 20:13.798
Rich is now hunting
for fresh tracks to chase.

20:13.833 --> 20:15.938
♪♪

20:15.973 --> 20:18.182
Rich: Rabbits, you can walk
right by them.

20:18.217 --> 20:19.597
You really got to look for them

20:19.632 --> 20:21.737
'cause sometimes they'll spook
and take off,

20:21.772 --> 20:23.049
but a lot of times
they're just froze

20:23.083 --> 20:25.983
and just sitting there
looking at you.

20:26.017 --> 20:27.674
[ Whispers ] Rabbit.

20:27.709 --> 20:36.062
♪♪

20:36.096 --> 20:38.582
He's got a den down in there.
There's a hole.

20:38.616 --> 20:40.446
Well, he's got him
a good home here.

20:40.480 --> 20:43.034
All this sage brush growing,
he's protected.

20:43.069 --> 20:44.829
Nothing can get down in there.

20:44.864 --> 20:51.664
♪♪

20:51.698 --> 20:53.113
I think I can get him
out of there.

20:53.148 --> 20:55.875
I'm going to make me
a little tepee here

20:55.909 --> 20:57.877
and try to smoke him
out of there.

20:57.911 --> 20:59.085
Could set a trap here.

20:59.119 --> 21:00.604
I know he's got to
come out of that hole.

21:00.638 --> 21:02.571
But I got some time to kill,

21:02.606 --> 21:04.504
and I want to get
some meat right now.

21:04.539 --> 21:07.507
♪♪

21:07.542 --> 21:08.543
I got some canvas.

21:08.577 --> 21:09.785
I'm gonna lay it over that

21:09.820 --> 21:11.994
and try to build a fire
on the back end.

21:12.029 --> 21:14.825
♪♪

21:14.859 --> 21:18.346
These little chips and just
sawdust -- best fire starter.

21:18.380 --> 21:21.349
This is a cotton ball
with Vaseline.

21:21.383 --> 21:27.665
♪♪

21:27.700 --> 21:30.737
This is gonna make it
smoke up really good.

21:30.772 --> 21:34.500
I just use juniper brush
to build up a bunch of smoke.

21:34.534 --> 21:39.539
♪♪

21:39.574 --> 21:41.921
She's starting to smoke now.

21:41.955 --> 21:44.130
I better get ready.

21:44.164 --> 21:46.719
That rabbit's gonna be
coming out of here before long.

21:46.753 --> 21:49.480
♪♪

21:49.515 --> 21:50.757
There it goes!

21:50.792 --> 21:54.313
♪♪

21:54.347 --> 21:56.349
He's got to be
right around here.

21:56.384 --> 22:01.458
♪♪

22:01.492 --> 22:02.562
There it is.

22:02.597 --> 22:07.118
♪♪

22:07.153 --> 22:08.396
[ Gunshot ]

22:08.430 --> 22:11.433
I wanted to make sure
and get a good, clean shot.

22:11.468 --> 22:12.538
I could have shot it
in the body,

22:12.572 --> 22:14.367
but then I'd ruin
half of the meat.

22:14.402 --> 22:21.167
♪♪

22:21.201 --> 22:24.135
All right.
I got some meat.

22:24.170 --> 22:27.311
I'm gonna go check my traps,
and hopefully I got a rabbit

22:27.346 --> 22:31.039
and I can have
a real good meal tonight.

22:31.073 --> 22:33.248
If I do have a rabbit, I don't
want it in the trap too long.

22:38.495 --> 22:40.082
Narrator: Coming up,
Marty's fight for meat

22:40.117 --> 22:42.119
Narrator: 30 miles
off Alaska's southern coast

22:42.153 --> 22:45.398
sits an island like no other --

22:45.433 --> 22:50.230
A 100-mile stretch of raw
wilderness known as Kodiak.

22:50.265 --> 22:54.476
Blanketed in thick clouds
and lush, dense forest,

22:54.511 --> 22:58.515
Kodiak is home to the largest
brown bears in the world,

22:58.549 --> 23:02.967
half-ton giants that prey
on the local wildlife,

23:03.002 --> 23:07.282
from salmon to foxes
and mountain goats,

23:07.316 --> 23:09.215
the same quarry
that Marty Meierotto

23:09.249 --> 23:11.320
has come here to hunt.

23:11.355 --> 23:13.288
Marty: I got a buddy
that lives in Kodiak,

23:13.322 --> 23:15.152
and he was making
a run down there.

23:15.186 --> 23:18.604
So having the opportunity,
I just thought I should take it.

23:18.638 --> 23:22.401
I really need more meat to get
through the rest of the year.

23:22.435 --> 23:25.265
Narrator:
10 weeks into one of his
lowest-producing winters ever,

23:25.300 --> 23:29.408
Marty has spent every minute
working to get out of the red.

23:29.442 --> 23:32.549
The relentless pace has left him
far behind on the hunt

23:32.583 --> 23:34.620
for winter meat.

23:34.654 --> 23:37.277
But this opportunity
comes with a catch.

23:37.312 --> 23:39.935
His return flight leaves
in two days' time,

23:39.970 --> 23:42.559
with or without him.

23:42.593 --> 23:44.561
Marty: On this goat hunt, I've
got a limited amount of time,

23:44.595 --> 23:48.012
so the strategy
is to drop me off

23:48.047 --> 23:49.807
in decent goat country

23:49.842 --> 23:51.602
and just see
if I can get to them.

23:51.637 --> 23:53.432
In goat hunting,
that's always the challenge

23:53.466 --> 23:56.469
is just seeing if you can get
to where they're at.

23:56.504 --> 23:59.230
Narrator: Mountain goats live
on the sheer rocky ledges

23:59.265 --> 24:02.371
of Kodiak's 4,000-foot peaks,

24:02.406 --> 24:05.478
where winds gust up
to 40 miles per hour.

24:05.513 --> 24:07.963
Marty: The wind right now
is blowing pretty hard.

24:07.998 --> 24:10.518
Real strong westerly,
so it's probably gonna be

24:10.552 --> 24:14.763
unbearable up there
on the mountain.

24:14.798 --> 24:17.904
Narrator: It's a 10-mile climb
to the top of the mountain,

24:17.939 --> 24:20.148
so Marty spends
the day's remaining hours

24:20.182 --> 24:22.702
scouting a clear route
for tomorrow.

24:22.737 --> 24:26.568
♪♪

24:26.603 --> 24:27.673
All right.

24:27.707 --> 24:29.191
This looks like a pretty
good vantage point

24:29.226 --> 24:32.298
for scoping
the goat rocks up there.

24:32.332 --> 24:39.512
♪♪

24:39.547 --> 24:45.138
Trouble with goats is they go
in places that no human can go.

24:45.173 --> 24:47.900
Some of them places up there,
if you slip and fall,

24:47.934 --> 24:50.109
you're gonna fall
for a long time.

24:50.143 --> 24:56.115
♪♪

24:56.149 --> 24:58.151
I think I see one.

25:00.429 --> 25:03.536
Got to be a goat.

25:03.571 --> 25:06.574
It is a goat.
It's moving.

25:06.608 --> 25:09.024
Wow.

25:09.059 --> 25:11.682
They are hard to see.

25:11.717 --> 25:14.651
♪♪

25:14.685 --> 25:16.480
Oh, there's another one.

25:16.515 --> 25:20.001
♪♪

25:20.035 --> 25:24.833
I think what I'm gonna do
early tomorrow,

25:24.868 --> 25:27.456
fight my way through
this bottom land

25:27.491 --> 25:31.253
and the brush and get up
on that ridge over there.

25:31.288 --> 25:36.638
And I'll chase that ridge up,
glass and all that.

25:36.673 --> 25:38.882
Narrator: Marty will need to get
an early start in the morning

25:38.916 --> 25:43.921
to make the most of just
six hours of daylight.

25:43.956 --> 25:47.511
Marty: That's about all I can
do for the day.

25:47.546 --> 25:50.756
Go back to camp, eat,
get a good night's sleep,

25:50.790 --> 25:53.897
and head out early,

25:53.931 --> 25:55.554
see if I can get up there.

25:55.588 --> 25:58.039
♪♪

25:59.972 --> 26:07.635
♪♪

26:07.669 --> 26:09.326
Narrator:
In the Northern Rockies,

26:09.360 --> 26:12.053
Tom's riding the momentum

26:12.087 --> 26:16.091
of the first productive season
he's had in several winters.

26:16.126 --> 26:18.853
Now with his living assured
for the year ahead,

26:18.887 --> 26:21.614
he's working to haul in
as much fur as possible

26:21.649 --> 26:24.548
to build a nest egg
for the future.

26:24.583 --> 26:28.448
You know, that's the object
is to make as much money

26:28.483 --> 26:33.384
as what you possibly can before
the trapping season ends.

26:33.419 --> 26:37.423
But it's really hard to get
around in this deep snow.

26:37.457 --> 26:39.943
We even felt the weather

26:39.977 --> 26:42.152
is starting to warm up
a little bit.

26:42.186 --> 26:46.328
We've still got over
three feet on the ground.

26:46.363 --> 26:48.503
Traveling is slower
on snowshoes.

26:48.537 --> 26:51.299
You're always stepping
[chuckling] high and long.

26:51.333 --> 26:53.335
It just makes it harder,

26:53.370 --> 26:55.752
but we still go check our traps

26:55.786 --> 26:57.788
no matter how hard it gets.

26:57.823 --> 26:59.687
Just like the mail's
got to go through,

26:59.721 --> 27:02.448
us trappers,
we got to do what we do.

27:02.482 --> 27:03.587
It's just part of life.

27:03.622 --> 27:06.210
You just live with
the weather up here,

27:06.245 --> 27:08.316
and don't cry about it,
you know?

27:08.350 --> 27:10.180
Just do it.

27:10.214 --> 27:13.804
Narrator: Tom's trekked one mile
deep along the Yaak River

27:13.839 --> 27:15.012
to a passageway

27:15.047 --> 27:17.705
that is known to produce
a bounty of beaver fur.

27:17.739 --> 27:20.224
This bend in the river
is a hot spot

27:20.259 --> 27:22.502
where the beaver travel
between their lodge

27:22.537 --> 27:26.541
and a rich cropping of one of
their favorite sources of food.

27:26.575 --> 27:29.440
Tom: There's lots of willow
and lots of red osier

27:29.475 --> 27:30.925
that the beavers eat.

27:30.959 --> 27:33.755
It's a pretty amazing thing
that such a big animal like that

27:33.790 --> 27:37.621
could only live off of just
the bark of trees, you know?

27:37.656 --> 27:42.971
♪♪

27:43.006 --> 27:45.491
Oh, we got one.

27:45.525 --> 27:50.703
♪♪

27:50.738 --> 27:52.222
All right.

27:54.120 --> 27:57.537
[ Grunts ]
This beaver is a 2-year-old.

27:57.572 --> 28:00.713
♪♪

28:00.748 --> 28:03.302
Good fur.

28:03.336 --> 28:08.928
He isn't real big,
but he has nice fur on him.

28:08.963 --> 28:12.760
They're sure super prime
this time of year.

28:12.794 --> 28:16.039
I'll reset this trap, put it
right back in the same spot.

28:16.073 --> 28:18.662
And hopefully we'll pick up
another beaver.

28:18.697 --> 28:21.285
There's only a few weeks
of the season left.

28:21.320 --> 28:23.978
But I'm not much for quitting.

28:24.012 --> 28:25.634
I made three catches.

28:25.669 --> 28:27.636
That's pretty good for a night.

28:27.671 --> 28:30.018
With the help that Sean's been,

28:30.053 --> 28:33.297
I think it's kind of working
to a real good season for me.

28:33.332 --> 28:43.307
♪♪

28:43.342 --> 28:48.105
♪♪

28:48.140 --> 28:52.247
Narrator: In Southwest Montana,
Rich has one rabbit in hand

28:52.282 --> 28:54.111
for tonight's dinner.

28:54.146 --> 28:57.736
And now he's checking his
pit trap in search of another.

29:00.048 --> 29:01.670
Rich:
If you're trapping for fur,

29:01.705 --> 29:03.500
you want to check them
every couple days.

29:03.534 --> 29:06.330
But rabbits, I'm gonna
check them a couple times a day

29:06.365 --> 29:09.299
because if I trap the rabbit,
if I leave it there too long,

29:09.333 --> 29:10.783
a predator will come right in

29:10.818 --> 29:13.061
and eat it, kill it,
take it away.

29:13.096 --> 29:19.309
♪♪

29:19.343 --> 29:21.104
Hey, something.
I got something.

29:21.138 --> 29:24.141
♪♪

29:24.176 --> 29:26.799
Heh-hoo! I got a rabbit!

29:26.834 --> 29:29.284
Whenever you're trapping,
you want to be humane

29:29.319 --> 29:30.769
and have respect for the animal.

29:30.803 --> 29:34.324
So you want to put it out of
its misery as fast as possible.

29:34.358 --> 29:36.636
Take care of him.[ Gun cocks ]

29:36.671 --> 29:38.569
♪♪

29:38.604 --> 29:40.123
[ Gunshot ]

29:40.157 --> 29:42.539
♪♪

29:42.573 --> 29:43.747
[ Grunts ]

29:43.782 --> 29:45.197
There's a lot of work
that went into this trap,

29:45.231 --> 29:49.442
but the nice thing about this is
I don't have any money in it.

29:49.477 --> 29:51.134
I can set this trap up again.

29:51.168 --> 29:54.793
I can keep using it
any time I want to.

29:54.827 --> 29:56.795
You know, everybody
has their ways of living.

29:56.829 --> 29:59.728
And this is my grocery store
right here.

29:59.763 --> 30:01.592
All right.
Got two rabbits.

30:01.627 --> 30:03.525
It's a lot of work to get
the food the way I do,

30:03.560 --> 30:05.631
but I wouldn't have it
any other way.

30:05.665 --> 30:11.292
♪♪

30:11.326 --> 30:11.775
Narrator:
Coming up, Brent battles
the cold as winter rages on.

30:11.810 --> 30:14.778
♪♪

30:14.813 --> 30:16.884
Narrator:
On Point Gustavus, Alaska,

30:16.918 --> 30:19.783
the storm that's already
dumped three inches of snow

30:19.818 --> 30:21.474
is still blowing,

30:21.509 --> 30:23.822
as Brent wraps us
his sixth straight hour

30:23.856 --> 30:26.031
of backbreaking labor.

30:26.065 --> 30:29.379
Brent:
This is my last rafter.

30:29.413 --> 30:30.829
Narrator: He is fighting
the onset of fatigue

30:30.863 --> 30:33.521
as he mounts
the last of the 100-pound boards

30:33.555 --> 30:35.903
that make up his cabin roof.

30:35.937 --> 30:39.976
But the final rafter is also
the most challenging to secure.

30:40.010 --> 30:42.806
♪♪

30:42.841 --> 30:44.843
Brent: This is bad weather.

30:44.877 --> 30:46.948
I don't have much
of an option right now.

30:46.983 --> 30:50.710
It's just an obstacle
that I've got to beat.

30:50.745 --> 30:56.993
♪♪

30:57.027 --> 30:58.753
All right.

30:58.787 --> 31:01.066
♪♪

31:01.100 --> 31:03.378
Well, we're getting closer.

31:03.413 --> 31:05.173
[ Hammering ]

31:05.208 --> 31:06.899
The bulk of the work is done,

31:06.934 --> 31:08.418
and I'm thankful
to have that done.

31:08.452 --> 31:11.835
But the scariest boards are the
ones I'm putting in right now.

31:11.870 --> 31:16.840
♪♪

31:16.875 --> 31:22.156
Get up there and nail the top in
without dying.

31:22.190 --> 31:24.365
It's been a long day.

31:24.399 --> 31:26.608
With the snow blowing
and ice accumulating

31:26.643 --> 31:29.128
on the floor of my loft
where my ladder is,

31:29.163 --> 31:31.786
I'm kind of in a war
between safety

31:31.820 --> 31:33.615
and getting this work done.

31:33.650 --> 31:37.205
I'm 30 feet off the ground,
and the wind's blowing.

31:39.587 --> 31:41.727
All right.

31:41.761 --> 31:44.557
Now my rafters are all in here
strong and secure.

31:44.592 --> 31:48.492
[ Wind howling ]

31:48.527 --> 31:50.046
Everything's well supported.

31:50.080 --> 31:52.669
So with all these in place now,

31:52.703 --> 31:55.465
it means that the wind's
not gonna blow them over

31:55.499 --> 31:57.329
and it's gonna stand strong.

31:57.363 --> 31:59.814
It's a nice one.

31:59.848 --> 32:02.092
I'm right on the edge
of a livable cabin.

32:02.127 --> 32:05.406
Once the plywood's on the roof
and plywood's on the walls,

32:05.440 --> 32:07.201
I'm gonna be able
to live in it.

32:07.235 --> 32:09.306
I've got to stay strong
and stay hungry

32:09.341 --> 32:10.756
for the work that's ahead of me.

32:10.790 --> 32:20.731
♪♪

32:20.766 --> 32:23.010
♪♪

32:23.044 --> 32:26.116
Narrator: In the
Great Alaska Range...

32:26.151 --> 32:28.636
♪♪

32:28.670 --> 32:30.949
Morgan: Looking good so far.

32:30.983 --> 32:34.331
I think I'm pretty well past
the overflow zone.

32:34.366 --> 32:36.230
Narrator: ...Morgan's fears
about the early melt

32:36.264 --> 32:40.441
delaying his critical
fuel drop may be premature.

32:40.475 --> 32:41.925
Morgan: Yeah.
That's good there.

32:41.960 --> 32:46.516
I mean, that's over a foot
of solid ice, so no problem.

32:46.550 --> 32:48.725
Narrator: A half-mile away
from the shoreline,

32:48.759 --> 32:50.589
the ice is thick enough
to support

32:50.623 --> 32:52.729
the weight of the delivery.

32:52.763 --> 32:57.976
Plane needs about 1,000 feet,
so I'll go down

32:58.010 --> 32:59.770
and cut a couple more
just to make sure

32:59.805 --> 33:02.670
things are consistent
along the length of the runway.

33:02.704 --> 33:03.947
And if it all looks good,

33:03.982 --> 33:06.570
I'm gonna put some spruce boughs
out there to mark it

33:06.605 --> 33:09.435
and then just a straight line
of spruce boughs.

33:09.470 --> 33:11.817
And that will tell the pilot
that I've walked the runway,

33:11.851 --> 33:15.510
and it will give him some
perspective on the white snow

33:15.545 --> 33:17.926
to let him know
where the good spot to land is.

33:17.961 --> 33:21.482
♪♪

33:21.516 --> 33:24.381
Wettest-looking spot I've seen,
so I'll try there,

33:24.416 --> 33:26.521
see if it's got
any water underneath it.

33:26.556 --> 33:30.353
[ Hammering ]

33:32.769 --> 33:34.874
Yeah.
Looks great there, too.

33:34.909 --> 33:40.846
♪♪

33:40.880 --> 33:44.850
It's probably 300, 400 yards.

33:44.884 --> 33:46.817
So plenty of room
for the plane to land.

33:46.852 --> 33:49.958
And the ice looks consistent
between here and there.

33:49.993 --> 33:51.960
It's, uh...

33:51.995 --> 33:54.273
lucky we didn't plan this
for a week later

33:54.308 --> 33:57.690
'cause the way that overflow
is starting to infiltrate,

33:57.725 --> 34:01.556
who knows, you know, when
this ice will just turn to slop.

34:01.591 --> 34:03.834
♪♪

34:03.869 --> 34:05.215
I'm getting cold out here
in this wind.

34:05.250 --> 34:06.734
I'm gonna go back
into the trees

34:06.768 --> 34:09.564
and get out of the wind
and get a fire going.

34:09.599 --> 34:15.777
♪♪

34:15.812 --> 34:22.094
♪♪

34:22.129 --> 34:24.717
All the wood's nice and dry.

34:24.752 --> 34:26.926
Makes starting a fire easy.

34:26.961 --> 34:29.757
♪♪

34:29.791 --> 34:32.380
I'm just gonna make myself
a nice big thick bed of boughs

34:32.415 --> 34:35.694
so I'm comfortable
up off the ground.

34:35.728 --> 34:38.214
And if I can get
a few hours of sleep,

34:38.248 --> 34:39.836
and wake up and feed the fire

34:39.870 --> 34:41.907
and get a few
more hours of sleep,

34:41.941 --> 34:45.013
that would be --
that would be plenty.

34:45.048 --> 34:46.187
[ Exhales deeply ]

34:46.222 --> 34:49.363
Takes a lot of boughs
and a lot of firewood

34:49.397 --> 34:52.193
to stay comfortable
for a night.

34:52.228 --> 34:57.992
I got a nice six inches or more
of boughs here.

34:58.026 --> 35:03.515
And all I can do now is wait,
let the sun go down.

35:03.549 --> 35:06.173
Hopefully it's good weather
for flying tomorrow morning.

35:06.207 --> 35:13.283
♪♪

35:13.318 --> 35:15.423
Narrator: Coming up...

35:15.458 --> 35:19.910
Narrator:
On Alaska's Kodiak Island,
Marty returns to camp

35:19.945 --> 35:22.706
with a game plan for tomorrow's
high-altitude goat hunt.

35:22.741 --> 35:26.779
♪♪

35:26.814 --> 35:30.128
Marty: There's no easy way
to get to a goat.

35:30.162 --> 35:31.853
Just hoping for decent weather.

35:31.888 --> 35:34.097
We'll see what tomorrow brings.

35:34.132 --> 35:38.722
♪♪

35:38.757 --> 35:39.999
Whoa.

35:40.034 --> 35:43.934
♪♪

35:43.969 --> 35:46.351
Big old brown bear track.

35:46.385 --> 35:50.631
♪♪

35:50.665 --> 35:52.805
Probably came right up
through here.

35:54.773 --> 35:56.395
You can see how big it is.

35:56.430 --> 35:58.949
♪♪

35:58.984 --> 36:00.951
That's a big track.

36:02.608 --> 36:05.577
This is exactly what
I didn't want to have happen.

36:05.611 --> 36:09.270
Probably say that's maybe
a 9-footer or so.

36:09.305 --> 36:11.203
[ Sighs ]

36:11.238 --> 36:13.757
Narrator: Kodiak bears
usually hibernate until April,

36:13.792 --> 36:17.761
but this bear is awake
a full month early,

36:17.796 --> 36:20.212
meaning it's likely
starved for calories

36:20.247 --> 36:22.973
and on the prowl for food.

36:23.008 --> 36:27.909
Marty:
The bears on Kodiak are a lot
bigger than the interior bears

36:27.944 --> 36:29.428
'cause they feed on fish.

36:29.463 --> 36:31.258
It's a high-protein diet.

36:31.292 --> 36:33.432
But there's no fish to be had
right now,

36:33.467 --> 36:35.883
so they're wandering around

36:35.917 --> 36:38.092
feeding on whatever stuff
they can find.

36:38.126 --> 36:40.991
Oh, he was...

36:41.026 --> 36:43.615
Looks like it was feeding
on a dead deer.

36:43.649 --> 36:50.138
♪♪

36:50.173 --> 36:53.003
There's bear poop there.

36:53.038 --> 36:59.389
And it looks like he's been
hanging out here quite a bit,

36:59.424 --> 37:01.322
laying around just eating.

37:03.497 --> 37:09.882
One, two, three,
four, five.

37:09.917 --> 37:11.850
Six.

37:11.884 --> 37:14.128
This isn't one deer.

37:14.162 --> 37:16.510
There's six legs just here.

37:16.544 --> 37:19.306
A bear had been stacking up
deer carcasses

37:19.340 --> 37:21.860
like 200 yards away
from my camp.

37:21.894 --> 37:26.968
♪♪

37:27.003 --> 37:28.901
But I don't know,
for whatever the reason

37:28.936 --> 37:31.525
the bear
is not around here anymore.

37:32.905 --> 37:36.046
I don't know where he went.

37:36.081 --> 37:38.808
I would have hated to have
walked into him on a kill.

37:38.842 --> 37:42.329
♪♪

37:42.363 --> 37:45.573
If you're on Kodiak, you're
gonna be dealing with bears.

37:45.608 --> 37:47.541
That's a given.

37:47.575 --> 37:51.338
They're big, and, you know, it's
always in the back of your mind.

37:53.581 --> 37:56.066
You don't want to camp
right on a bear trail

37:56.101 --> 37:59.000
'cause you're just asking
for trouble.

37:59.035 --> 38:09.079
♪♪

38:09.114 --> 38:14.740
♪♪

38:14.775 --> 38:19.607
Narrator:
In the Yaak, Tom returns home
with a truck full of pelts.

38:19.642 --> 38:24.509
No stranger to lean times,
he's savoring the victory.

38:24.543 --> 38:27.546
Tom: It's always a good feeling
to have a successful day

38:27.581 --> 38:29.134
on the trapline, you know,

38:29.168 --> 38:33.172
'cause there's lots of days
that aren't successful at all.

38:33.207 --> 38:36.348
When you have a good one,
you always appreciate it.

38:36.383 --> 38:38.730
Part of the game of trapping.

38:38.764 --> 38:44.943
♪♪

38:44.977 --> 38:46.496
Hey.
Hi.

38:46.531 --> 38:47.704
How'd it go?

38:47.739 --> 38:48.774
It went pretty good.

38:48.809 --> 38:50.673
I got a beaver,
and I got two muskrats.

38:50.707 --> 38:51.881
Oh, very good.

38:51.915 --> 38:54.332
So it's a start, anyhow,
for that hat order.

38:54.366 --> 38:56.782
Let me see.

38:56.817 --> 38:58.439
Check out what you got
in there.

38:58.474 --> 39:00.855
All right.

39:00.890 --> 39:03.030
All right.We got a couple of them,
anyhow.

39:03.064 --> 39:05.170
Yeah.
Good deal.

39:05.204 --> 39:06.654
Very good job, honey.

39:06.689 --> 39:07.931
Yeah.
All right.

39:07.966 --> 39:09.864
You probably got a cup
of coffee there too, huh?

39:09.899 --> 39:12.004
[ Laughs ] Yes.

39:12.039 --> 39:14.179
When Tom comes home
and he's been successful

39:14.213 --> 39:15.836
and he's got something,

39:15.870 --> 39:17.941
it's very exciting.

39:17.976 --> 39:19.943
Narrator: While Tom's been out
running the line,

39:19.978 --> 39:23.257
Nancy's been peeling
and shaping willow branches.

39:23.291 --> 39:26.467
On their own, beaver pelts
only sell for $30.

39:26.502 --> 39:28.331
But once tanned by Tom,

39:28.366 --> 39:31.196
and mounted on one
of Nancy's hand crafted hoops,

39:31.230 --> 39:33.578
they're worth $250 a piece.

39:33.612 --> 39:36.028
Tom: That's what I have to do
to make a living, really.

39:36.063 --> 39:39.584
Because if I'm selling my furs
to the raw fur trade,

39:39.618 --> 39:41.586
I'm not making gas money.

39:43.484 --> 39:44.589
[ Dog barks ]

39:44.623 --> 39:46.038
Well, here comes Sean.

39:46.073 --> 39:47.281
Nancy: All right.

39:47.315 --> 39:50.180
♪♪

39:50.215 --> 39:52.182
-Well, congratulations.
-Look at you.

39:52.217 --> 39:55.427
-You had a good day, huh?
-We did have a good day.

39:55.462 --> 39:57.878
-All right.
-What do you think of that?

39:57.912 --> 40:00.294
Tom:
Pretty darn good, huh?

40:00.328 --> 40:02.330
So ran the trapline
on the Kootenai today

40:02.365 --> 40:05.437
and was able to pick up
a couple extra beavers.

40:05.472 --> 40:07.128
Tom's real happy
with seeing a couple

40:07.163 --> 40:08.923
more skins
come in this evening.

40:08.958 --> 40:11.961
-Yeah. Good going, good going.
-Look at those beavers.

40:11.995 --> 40:13.756
What do you think
of that, Ellie?

40:13.790 --> 40:15.033
Nancy: "Oh, I like it."

40:15.067 --> 40:16.517
Ellie likes them, yeah.

40:16.552 --> 40:17.553
Good job.

40:17.587 --> 40:18.830
Yeah, pretty cool.

40:18.864 --> 40:20.348
I better keep peeling.

40:20.383 --> 40:22.661
Tom: We're gonna have a great
big pile of fur this year...

40:22.696 --> 40:24.180
I hope so, yeah....it looks like,
if this keeps coming in.

40:24.214 --> 40:25.664
[ Laughs ]

40:25.699 --> 40:26.872
Got some skinning
to do, though.

40:26.907 --> 40:28.184
Yeah.
Maybe we should...

40:28.218 --> 40:29.634
You want a little help?

40:29.668 --> 40:31.049
I could use a little help,
maybe.

40:31.083 --> 40:32.982
Sure.

40:33.016 --> 40:33.810
Nancy: Good job, Sean.

40:33.845 --> 40:35.018
All right.
Good job.

40:35.053 --> 40:36.261
Sean: Well, Nance, you know
where we'll be.

40:36.295 --> 40:38.332
Nancy: Yes, I do.
And I'll be right here peeling.

40:38.366 --> 40:39.540
Okay, we'll see you
in a little bit.

40:39.575 --> 40:40.610
All right.

40:40.645 --> 40:41.784
Don't cut any holes.

40:41.818 --> 40:43.406
Tom: We'll try not to.

40:43.441 --> 40:44.718
I think he's hooked.

40:44.752 --> 40:47.168
I think he's really hooked
on this trapping thing.

40:47.203 --> 40:48.929
It's good to see a young person

40:48.963 --> 40:52.726
with excitement
about the trapping.

40:52.760 --> 40:54.452
♪♪

40:54.486 --> 40:56.419
Narrator:
Next time on "Mountain Men"...

40:56.454 --> 40:57.834
Marty:
I'm gonna head right at them

40:57.869 --> 40:59.560
'cause that's my only option.

40:59.595 --> 41:01.320
Narrator: ...Marty's hunt
takes him to the top

41:01.355 --> 41:03.288
of Kodiak's iciest peaks...

41:03.322 --> 41:05.601
Marty: You know, you slip
and fall up there,

41:05.635 --> 41:07.810
you could fall for a long ways.

41:07.844 --> 41:10.606
Narrator: ...Jason gets hit
in the line of fire...

41:10.640 --> 41:13.850
Ah. [Bleep]

41:13.885 --> 41:16.439
...and racing
against the melt...

41:16.474 --> 41:20.270
Morgan:
It looks like a big section
of this creek's dropped out.

41:20.305 --> 41:22.687
Narrator: ...Morgan slips up.

41:22.721 --> 41:23.688
Morgan: Damn it. Damn it.
Damn it.

41:23.722 --> 41:25.621
[Bleep] [Bleep] [Bleep]

41:25.655 --> 41:27.519
Oh, damn it!

41:27.554 --> 41:28.900
It went under.

41:28.934 --> 41:31.143
♪♪
